[{"id":"VR022370","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR022339.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of an anion with a negative 1 charge next to an N a ion with a positive one charge. There is a Lewis diagram of the anion. There is a row of atoms, N, C, and C, connected by single bonds. The N atom is connected to two H atoms, each by a single bond, and has a nonbonding pair of electrons. The C atom on the left is connected to two H atoms by single bonds. The C atom on the right is connected to two O atoms, one by a single bond, and the other by a double bond. The O atom connected by a single bond has three nonbonding pairs of electrons, and the O atom connected by a double bond has two nonbonding pairs of electrons. The structure of the anion has brackets around it, and there is a minus sign at the top right, indicating that the species has a negative one charge.\" height=\"130\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR022370.g01.png\" width=\"250\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following statements is true about sodium glycinate, represented above?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR022370_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a Lewis diagram of a glycinium cation with a positive 1 charge. There is a row of atoms, H, N, C, C, O, and H connected with single bonds. The N atom is connected to two additional H atoms with single bonds. The C atom on the left is connected to two H atoms with single bonds. The C atom on the right is connected to an additional O atom with a double bond. Both O atoms have two nonbonding pairs of electrons. The structure has brackets around it, and there is a plus sign at the top right, indicating that the species has a positive one charge. The leftmost H atom is labeled p K sub a equals 9.6. The rightmost H atom is labeled p K sub a equals 2.3.\" height=\"119\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR022339.g01.png\" width=\"225\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The structural formula of the glycinium cation is shown above. Arrows indicate the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"p K sub a\"><math alttext=\"p K sub a\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>p</mtext><msub><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> values for the labile protons in the molecule.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It is an ionic solid at room temperature.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It is not soluble in water.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It evaporates easily because of the lack of hydrogen bonding.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It dissolves in water to form an acidic solution.</p>"],"answer":0}]